Introduction\
Outlier detection is an essential part of data analysis, as it helps identify anomalies or rare observations in a dataset that do not conform to the expected pattern. These outliers can have a significant impact on the results of data analysis and predictive modeling, so detecting them early is crucial. In this blog, we will discuss what outliers are, why they matter, and various techniques for detecting them.\
\
What are Outliers?\
\
Outliers are data points that significantly differ from the majority of the data. They can be unusually high or low values that do not follow the established trend in the dataset. Outliers can result from errors in data collection, unusual occurrences, or genuine variability in the data.\
	1.	Types of Outliers\
	\'95	Point Outliers: These are single data points that deviate significantly from the rest of the dataset.\
	\'95	Contextual Outliers: These are data points that are considered outliers only in a specific context. For example, an unusually high temperature may be an outlier in winter but normal in summer.\
	\'95	Collective Outliers: A set of data points that are anomalous together, even though individual points may not be outliers.\
	2.	Examples of Outliers\
	\'95	A high-value transaction in a bank dataset could be an outlier compared to other normal transactions.\
	\'95	Unusual medical test results that differ drastically from the rest of the data.\
\
Why is Outlier Detection Important?\
	1.	Data Quality\
Outliers can distort the results of statistical analyses, skewing the mean or variance and leading to incorrect conclusions.\
	2.	Model Accuracy\
In machine learning, outliers can negatively impact the accuracy of models, especially regression models, and affect the performance of clustering and classification algorithms.\
	3.	Anomaly Detection\
Outlier detection can be used as an anomaly detection technique in various domains, such as fraud detection, network security, and quality control.\
\
